<td><FONT SIZE="1" FACE="Verdana, Arial" COLOR="#871f78">Originally posted by Aperaisal Shadowdancer on 12-18-2000 07:09 PM<BR></FONT>
<TEXTAREA NAME="EditedMessage" ROWS=10 COLS=45 WRAP="VIRTUAL">  I would say that points made on both sides of this have validity, but I think that fair play rules should only be invoked in the worst situations as it is a policy that is too easly abused or used for ones own gain.  EQ is a large (300,000+ last I heard) and diverse culture of players from all walks of life and as such (excepting the good roleplayers to a lesser or greater degree) project their personal styles(the good, the bad and the ugly), wants(loot and level, high adventure), and desires(A fist full of dollars, and a few more, ect..) in the game.  This is human nature, over all I think the EQ community has done a good job of self regulating play.  
  If there be fault to lay, I would lay it at Veriants doorstep.  They have established the level of loot value/trading vs exploring/adventuring.  EQ has the beginings of a rich storyline that is wasted by it's unchanging state, no amount of exploring/adventuring, valiant deeds or villainous acts will ever change it.  BUT, the player(you) can effect the value of loot or trade goods, hence less adventure more loot camps.  Also I beleave Veriant is taking the easy way out of the delimma as their primary responce to any conflict is to nerf the relivant drop or spawn.  
  Anyway thats my soapbox stance.  Good gaming to you all. ;)</TEXTAREA>
</td></tr>
